<br>
By The NuclearSpace.com Team.<br>
<br>
There was a time once when we were all about exploration, conquest and colonization - we can now be defined as a civilization that focuses on internal problems that will or can never be completely solved. <br>
<br>
A cold shudder or chill may go up your spine looking at old black and white photographs of people, events, machines, inventions, proposals and visionary schemes from the early half of the century. <br>
<br>
To see what could have and should have been is sobering to say the least. That generation of yesteryear believed so firmly in science, technology and the progress of Western Man in all areas of life, it is easy to see why they have been called The Greatest Generation. They believed that science (understanding) and technology (application) would lead to a higher standard of living, which it did. They believed in letting technology solve its own problems. They believed in grand projects of engineering.<br>
<br>
Where did we go wrong? Why did we change?<br>
<br>
Prometheus was the Titan who in ancient Greek mythology stole fire from the Gods and then gave it to mankind. It is also the name of Nasa's new Nuclear Space Initiative and is therefore rather apt. To primitive man, fire was perhaps the most fearful elemental force in the natural World. All beasts ran before it and only the swift survived. It was a rare occurence sometimes sparked by lightning strikes, frequently engulfing vast forests and many villages in flame when it struck. It consumed all and left nothing but ash. Wild animals have a primeval fear of it which triggers their flight reflex and early man would have been little different. There must have been a time, tens of thousands of years ago, when early humans began to realise they could gain mastery over this terror. We can imagine a tribal meeting arguing the pro's and con's of experimenting with such a deadly killer. Of opening that Pandora's box. No doubt it was a difficult decision fraught with powerful arguments. <br>
<br>
&quot;It is taboo to make fire. You will kill us all.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;We can heat our homes in winter and cook our food.&quot;<br>
<br>
We all know the result. Progress won out in the end. There were disasters along the way where entire cities were burned to the ground, but more was gained than lost by harnessing fire. Nobody would ever suggest we made the wrong decision or that we should turn back the clock. If we had chosen to ban fire then we would probably still be living in the stone age. Don't laugh. That first accidental discovery of how to create fire might easily have been buried by frightened elders in some long forgotten era. It's full possibilities might never have been realised. <br>
<br>
Technology that is banned by any nation invariably comes back to bite it in the rear. The British virtually outlawed cars at the turn of the century in favour of hoofs. The British Car industry has never really caught up with Europe or the US as a consequence. Again, the British Naval Admiralty saw no value in submarines. Much to the glee of German U-boat Commanders decades later on. If the Chinese had looked just a little more closely at the possibilities of their fireworks, those entertaining toys which so lit up the eyes of their children, they would not have been so surprised by the oncoming Western forces carrying repeater rifles. Instead of western powers dominating World History it might have been Asia instead. <br>
<br>
Anything of importance we ban or ignore will be researched elsewhere. This is a fact. Also, the results of that work will be mostly unknown to us until the terrifying moment that it is used against us. This commonsense logic applies to any technology but the consequences of turning our backs on the most cutting edge sciences available to us is particularly frightening. <br>
<br>
Opposition movements to nuclear power in space are fond of fearmongering. Often associated with conspiracy theorists and anti-technologists, their arguments fall into two shallow categories. Gutter science which is easily disproved or simply accusing Nasa and others of lying.<br>
<br>
Here are some examples from the Global Network Against Weapons And Nuclear Power In Space.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In 1997 NASA launched the Cassini space probe carrying 72 pounds of plutonium that fortunately did not experience failure. If it had, hundreds of thousands of people around the world could have been contaminated.&quot;<br>
<br>
How can you cite a success as a failure? This is true 'spin' doctoring. Hundreds of thousands contaminated? What is his risk mitigation source for that statement? The actual available evidence indicates that the worstcase scenario would be unlikely to cause even a single fatality. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;Beyond accidents impacting the planet, the space nuclear production process at the DoE labs will lead to significant numbers of workers and communities being contaminated.&quot; <br>
<br>
Beer is 13 times more radioactive than the cooling water discharged from a nuclear power plant. We are contaminated every time we walk out into the sun. By not giving contamination levels it is an empty statement. The number one source of man made radiation released into the environment is in the form of X-ray diagnostics from hospitals. Far outsripping fallout, Chernobyl and all others combined. Shall we ban hospitals then? Safety regulations administering the operation of nuclear plants are already excessively stringent. If the White House was a nuclear power plant it would probably be closed down due to excessive radioactivity in it's walls. They are known to contain naturally occuring Uranium. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;...the NASA space nukes initiative represents the Bush administration's covert move to develop power systems for space-based weapons such as lasers on satellites. The military has often stated that their planned lasers in space will require enormous power projection capability and that nuclear reactors in orbit...&quot; <br>
<br>
Wrong. The military abandoned it's nuclear space reactor (SP-100) in the 80's. Nothing covert or secretive about the military's space based reactor research or about SDI, it was in the news frequently in the mid-late 80's. This information is simply 20 years out of date. I'm not familiar with any current plans to place a laser in space as a weapon? Anyone else know anything about this that is factual?<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA's nuclear rocket is a Trojan horse for the militarization of space.&quot;<br>
<br>
Technically it's assumed to be a reactor powered ion engine, not a nuclear rocket. NASA is a civilian agency and differentiated from the military. Ofcourse, the militarisation of space is eventually going to happen. The Air Force routinely flies aircraft at the edge of space. The prospect of others using space as a weapons launchpad is sufficient reason to expect that the military will play a key role at some point. In today's terrorist plagued World it seems a sensible decision to me.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In the end hundreds and hundreds of billions of dollars will be wasted on plans for the nuclearization and weaponization of space.&quot;<br>
<br>
How does he know this? Can the author provide a budget line item that has these figures? No. Because it's a flawed statement, an 'assumption'. Perhaps a quote on the market value of one moderate sized iron ore asteroid would fit in here nicely? Eros is estimated to be worth around 40 trillion dollars US. It's true that Nasa has a zero profit policy but they will be opening the door for others by showing the way. The wealth which could be generated by opening up the final frontier is incalculable. Tourism, resources, energy production etc.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;Their plans now literally threaten the life of the entire planetary ecosystem.&quot;<br>
<br>
Doomsday scare tactics with no real science to back up the claim. Hundreds of high megaton nuclear bomb tests from the 50's and 60's released tons of Plutonium and highly enriched Uranium directly into the atmosphere and I would like to point out how the Earth did NOT become a wasteland as a result. The last launch of Plutonium by Nasa was Cassini back in 97 and the possibility of a launch failure was well planned for. The fuel was so well encased it would likely have been picked up and reused in a later mission if an unlikely accident had occured. But the launch went without a hitch, much to the disapointment of protestors. The next planned nuclear launch this Summer will carry 16 penny sized pellets of Plutonium for the twin Mars Rovers and every precaution is again being taken. It is ridiculous to hype up the miniscule danger of radioactive release for such missions when coal plants routinely burn up thousands of tons of Uranium and Thorium found in coal beds, then pump it straight into our atmosphere. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;Ultimately NASA envisions mining colonies on the Moon, Mars, and asteroids that would be powered by nuclear reactors.&quot;<br>
<br>
This has never been NASA's goal, this is simply an &quot;untruth&quot;. As a non-profit organisation Nasa is largely restricted to exploration.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;All of the above missions would be launched from the Kennedy Space Center in Florida on rockets with a historic 10% failure rate. &quot; <br>
<br>
I believe the shuttle's failure rate is about 1 failure for<br>
every 200 launches, this is simply extremist, ignorant rhetoric. A failure does not automatically mean a big fireball on the pad. Most failures are simply cancellations.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In April, 1964 a U.S. military satellite with 2.1 pounds of plutonium-238 on-board fell back to Earth and burned up as it hit the atmosphere spreading the toxic plutonium globally as dust to be ingested by the people of the planet.&quot;<br>
<br>
This is a purposefully misleading statement, the SNAP-9A RTG was an old 1960's design. The redesigned RTG's that launched after this have proven their safety with no release of radioactive elements despite two instances of catastrophic rocket failure. The newer designs have PROVED <br>
that they are safe even under the most extreme abuse. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;During the Cassini RTG fabrication process at Los Alamos 244 cases of worker contamination were reported to the DoE.&quot;<br>
<br>
And this killed how many people? This is being purposefully misleading.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;the NASA space nukes initiative represents the Bush administration's covert move to develop power systems for space-based weapons such as lasers on satellites. &quot; <br>
<br>
This unsubstantiated claim again. Even if true....So what? Space is not an environmental preserve for peaceniks.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In order to fund these missions Bush and Congress will have to cut programs like social security, education, health care, child care, public transit and environmental protection. &quot;<br>
<br>
Of course, we can only spend money on your pet social pork programs. If any leader spouts this nonsense to me, they've lost my vote. It's the tired old argument of 'why do we spend money in space when people are starving here on earth?', that those against science and progress like to bring up repeatedly. The ancestors of these people are the ones who spoke against playing around with fire. &quot;It&quot;s a waste of time. It will never lead anywhere. Forget about it. There are important things to do like picking berries from bushes and fleas from our scalps.&quot;<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;During the 1950s and 1960s NASA spent over $10 billion to build the nuclear rocket program which was cancelled in the end because of the fear that a launch accident would contaminate major portions of Florida and beyond.&quot;<br>
<br>
This is completely untrue. It was actually cancelled because Americans lost interest in a Mars Mission. Mr Gagnon is giving his fellow protestors an undeserved pat on the back here. The radiological release from NTR test firings was considered so minimal that the nozzles were pointed upwards. When nuclear weapons tests were being banned, nuclear thermal rockets quietly faded away along with our enthusiasm for space.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA hasn't learned its lesson from its history involving space nuclear power,&quot; says Kaku, &quot;and a hallmark of science is that you learn from previous mistakes. NASA doggedly pursues its fantasy of nuclear power in space.&quot;<br>
<br>
What lesson is that? The only mistake was cancelling the program. Nuclear power is the only sensible option for manned space missions. Hence a return to it. The only fantasy being doggedly pursued is the one Michio Kaku preaches. That solar power can do the job for us. It's a nonsensical claim. The most impractical suggestion there is for space based energy production for serious missions. Particularly in the outer reaches of the solar system where light is thousands of times dimmer.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA, DoE, and the Pentagon are not asking the tax paying public if we want to suffer the risk and costs of nuclear power in space.&quot;<br>
<br>
I would welcome a public opinion poll asking this very question. There was one at Space.com a couple of years ago. It had the largest response in the history of the site. Well over 95% approval for a nuclear space initiative. Bruce Gagnon has always claimed to speak for the masses but I have yet to see any evidence to back this assumption on his part.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA says that poses a 1-in-1,030 possibility of a radioactive accident near the launch site and, even in the worst-case scenario, the most exposed individuals would be subjected to less radiation than a single medical X-ray. &quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;NASA is lying,&quot; said Bruce Gagnon.<br>
<br>
